                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.01 Caffery Mission/10: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in El Salvador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Curtis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-28T12:00:00-06:00"
                            >December 28, 1931—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 2:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>127. From Caffery. Legation’s telegram No. 124, December 23, 6 p.m., first two
                    sentences of second paragraph. Castaneda insistently desires that I consult the
                    Department regarding his somewhat original thesis that the word “election”
                    refers only to popular elections for President and not to elections by the
                    Assembly.</p>
                <p>The military remain in complete control of the situation and firmly back up
                    Martínez and Castaneda. [Caffery.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Curtis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
